HttpHead class. MIT (c) 2020-2025 miktim@mail.ru

Read/write/store HTTP message head.
HTTP head is a request/status line (start line), header fields (headers)
and the trailing empty line.

Release notes:
  - the header names ara case-insensitive;
  - multiple header values are stored on one line separated by commas;
  - the following header values are treated as multiple values:
      Expires: Wed, 01 Jun 2022 08:00:00 GMT
      Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate
      Cache-Control: no-cache, no-store, must-revalidate
    and so on;
  - without any data control.

package org.miktim.http;

Overview:

  Class HttpHead extends TreeMap<String, String>;

    Constructors:
      HttpHead();
      HttpHead(Map<String,String> map); // duplicates head
      
    Methods:
      static String join(String[] s, String separator);
        - joins strings with separator 
          (the antonym for the Java String.split method)

      HttpHead setStartLine(String line);
        - sets http request/status line
      String getStartLine();
        - returns http start line

      String[] listHeaders();
        - returns list of header names
      HttpHead set(String header, String value);
        - creates or overwrites header value
      HttpHead add(String header, String value);
        - creates header or add comma separeted value
      HttpHead setValues(String header, String[] values);
        - creates or overwrite header with values
      String[] listValues(String header);
        - returns array of header values
      String get(String header);
        - inherited;
        - returns header comma separated values or null
      String remove(String header);
        - inherited;
        - remove header, returns header value or null
      boolean exists(String header);
        - checks for the header

      HttpHead read(InputStream is) throws IOException;
        - reads the http head and trailing blank line
          from the input stream
      void write(OutputStream os) throws IOException;
        - writes http head to the output stream and flushes it. 

      String toString();
        - returns http header with a start line,
          headers and a trailing blank line
      
Usage:
  See WebSocket package WsHandshake class handshakeClient, handshakeServer methods.
